        <div class="w-richtext">
          <h2>Design Process</h2>
          <h3 id="persona-development">Persona Development</h3>
          <p>Since Canopy was newly launched, it was still exploring specifics of its ideal user base. We did not have concrete data so we predicted what kind of user would be ideal for the product with a provisional persona.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="w-inline-block w-lightbox" href="#"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/canopy persona.png" width="60%">
          <script class="w-json" type="application/json">
            { "items": [{
              "_id": "577eb07b7c62eea72045d2a7",
              "cdnUrl": "https://daks2k3a4ib2z.cloudfront.net/571abfc80a8819820933b957/577eb07b7c62eea72045d2a7_canopy%20persona.png",
              "fileName": "canopy persona.png",
              "origFileName": "canopy persona.png",
              "width": 800,
              "height": 1126,
              "fileSize": 301469,
              "type": "image",
              "url": "../images/canopy persona.png"
            }] }
          </script>
        </a>
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>To ensure our persona held some accuracy, we conducted user interviews with people who used Canopy or had an interest to learn stock-trading. We validated their behaviors and needs for learning stocks, and asked them comprehension questions regarding their learning styles and previous experiences.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_7283.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>We found 4 key insights from this process:</p>
          <p>1. Users wanted short, bite-sized lessons when learning new material
            <br>2.&nbsp;Users wanted elements of interactivity within the lesson to keep them engaged
            <br>3. Users wanted structure to their learning process
            <br>4.&nbsp;Users were unsure what level they were considered regarding knowledge of material</p>
          <h3 id="industry-research">Industry Research</h3>
          <p>We also started researching best practices for the learning platform industry. We examined successful models, such as Duolingo and Codecademy, to discover which attributes they had in common and to figure out which methodologies were considered most effective.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_4302.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>We noted pros and cons for each platform and agreed upon which we thought had potential to be best suited for Canopy.</p>
          <h3 id="ideation">Ideation</h3>
          <p>With our persona’s needs and industry inspirations in mind, we started our extended version of the&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.gv.com/sprint/">Google Ventures Design Sprint</a>. Normally, this whole process would be conducted in a week, but instead, we spanned this over the course of a couple weeks.</p>
          <p>We started with an idea dump of all possible directions we can take in order to create an engaging learning platform for users. We listed out our ideas and narrowed in on the best and most feasible ideas. We further narrowed our scope to what we wanted to accomplish for the primary version of the web application.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/2016-04-13 17.02.48.jpg" width="80%"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/2016-04-19 15.55.18.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>Next, we moved on to Crazy 8’s, an activity where we sketched 8 lo-fi variations of our design ideas in 5 minutes. We did this on the primary screens we were going to focus on: the course roadmap and the lesson page, focusing on designing&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="https://abookapart.com/products/mobile-first">mobile first</a>.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_4303.jpg" width="80%"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_4312.jpg" width="80%"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_4313.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>We gathered insight from each other’s work and continued on to sketch out a full-page layout, one for the roadmap and one for the lesson. I decided to focus on the lesson page, and helped create the baseline for the final product.</p>
          <h3 id="prototype">Prototype</h3>
          <p>We started our prototyping process by first diverging and creating 3 separate wireframe designs for the course roadmap and the lesson page.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="w-inline-block w-lightbox" href="#"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/designs diverged.png" width="80%">
          <script class="w-json" type="application/json">
            { "items": [{
              "_id": "577eb41e7c62eea7204605f6",
              "cdnUrl": "https://daks2k3a4ib2z.cloudfront.net/571abfc80a8819820933b957/577eb41e7c62eea7204605f6_designs%20diverged.png",
              "fileName": "designs diverged.png",
              "origFileName": "designs diverged.png",
              "width": 1189,
              "height": 601,
              "fileSize": 189488,
              "type": "image",
              "url": "../images/designs diverged.png"
            }] }
          </script>
        </a>
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>Along with one of the founders of Canopy, we performed a design review to gather feedback and to ensure our works were aligning with the overall vision, look, and feel of the product.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/IMG_7425.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>We critiqued each screen and split into 2 teams dedicated to the course roadmap and lesson page. In our teams, we converged on a singular design we decided would solve the problem in the best way.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="w-inline-block w-lightbox" href="#"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/designs converged.png" width="80%">
          <script class="w-json" type="application/json">
            { "items": [{
              "_id": "577eb4f0f41531c220ef3308",
              "cdnUrl": "https://daks2k3a4ib2z.cloudfront.net/571abfc80a8819820933b957/577eb4f0f41531c220ef3308_designs%20converged.png",
              "fileName": "designs converged.png",
              "origFileName": "designs converged.png",
              "width": 1091,
              "height": 593,
              "fileSize": 179667,
              "type": "image",
              "url": "../images/designs converged.png"
            }] }
          </script>
        </a>
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>We came together to ensure the two ideas flowed cohesively and that all UI elements were&nbsp;scaleable to desktop web.</p>
          <p>We populated our mockups with dummy information and created a mid-fidelity prototype using Pixate.</p>
          <h3 id="usability-testing">Usability Testing</h3>
          <p>We tested our prototype with 6 users. Although 7 users would have provided more statistical significance, the result from testing 6 users was enough to inform our next steps in the process. We walked users through completing a lesson in our prototype, and asked them a couple of comprehension questions.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/Canopy Testing 1.png" width="60%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>Unfortunately, most of the confusion from our&nbsp;users came from misunderstanding the dummy content&nbsp;in the prototype. We immediately&nbsp;remedied this by using more relevant copy and iconography in our next iteration.</p>
          <p>Despite this, there were some aspects that went incredibly well: all users understood it was a learning platform, knew how to start a lesson, and liked the interactivity within the lesson. For everything else, we mapped out all the pain points we needed to address for our next iteration.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/2016-05-10 17.15.27.jpg" width="80%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <h3 id="iteration">Iteration</h3>
          <p>Before our next round of testing, we split up and made the appropriate changes to our prototype from the results of our first testing. To combat the confusion with our dummy copy and iconography, we also took our designs into high fidelity.</p>
          <p>For consistency, we tested another group of 6 users.</p>
        </div><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/Canopy Testing 2.png" width="60%">
        <div class="w-richtext">
          <p>These results were much more agreeable and from here, we only made minor changes to our prototype before the final deliverable.</p>
          <p>One thing we had to unquestionably address was our “cheat sheet.”&nbsp;Although our comprehension testing told us users enjoyed the idea of having a lesson summary, “cheat sheet” was indecipherable to users. We decided to simply rename this as “lesson summary” for our next iteration.</p>
          <p>Here are some screen examples of the evolution of our prototypes. Click through for larger image.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="w-inline-block w-lightbox" href="#"><img class="project-body-image" src="../images/Canopy Changes.png" width="80%">
          <script class="w-json" type="application/json">
