        <div class="w-richtext">
          <h3>Next Steps</h3>
          <p>We handed our work over to the Canopy team, including secondary login and profile screens to complete the ecosystem. For next steps, we encouraged the team to:</p>
          <p>1. Conduct another round of testing using “lesson summary” instead of “cheat sheet” to confirm users' understanding
            <br>2. Arrange lessons by topic to resonate with users who do not know their level of knowledge
            <br>3. Build out other pages, including the login and profile pages, to match the look and feel of the new platform</p>
          <p>The Canopy is now working on implementing the changes we have proposed, and you can check it out&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.canopytrading.com/">here</a>!</p>
          <h2>Reflection</h2>
          <p>Working on Canopy taught me how to thrive working in ambiguous circumstances. Being a very early stage product, the founders were very flexible. Although this made them extremely receptive to our ideas, it was challenging optimizing designs for an indistinct product. Ultimately, we learned how to&nbsp;ask for concrete answers to narrow the scope of our solutions.</p>
          <p>Working with clients also&nbsp;taught me how to effectively communicate design decisions. I learned to be careful not to use jargon and to explain only things in ways non-designers can digest. Additionally, it is most helpful to limit options as to not overwhelm them and to have conviction as we deliver the final result. Ultimately, the client trusted us with design decisions, so we took the lead and spoke with confidence.</p>
        </div>
